<ContentLayout
  title="Best White Label Website Audit Tools for Agencies"
  description="Compare the best white-label website audit tools that let agencies deliver branded audit reports to clients. Covers features, pricing, customisation, and how to sell audit services."
  breadcrumbs={breadcrumbs}
  toc={toc}
  publishDate="2026-03-28"
>
  <p>White-label audit tools allow digital agencies to run comprehensive website audits and deliver the results under their own brand. The client sees a polished, branded report from their agency — not a generic output from a third-party tool. This capability is essential for agencies that offer SEO services because audits are a cornerstone of client onboarding, quarterly reviews, and new business proposals.</p>

  <p>The market for white-label audit tools has matured significantly. Five years ago, options were limited and the branding was superficial — a logo slapped on a template. Today, the best tools offer deep customisation, automated scheduling, client portal access, and report quality that rivals what a senior analyst would produce manually. The trade-off is that white-label features typically sit on higher-tier pricing plans, so agencies need to calculate whether the time savings justify the cost compared to producing reports manually.</p>

  <p>This guide evaluates the leading white-label audit tools, compares their features and pricing, and provides a framework for agencies looking to sell audit services as a standalone offering or as part of a broader SEO retainer.</p>

  <h2 id="what-is-white-label-auditing">What Is White Label Auditing</h2>

  <p>White-label auditing means conducting a website audit using a third-party tool but presenting the results to your client as if the work was performed entirely by your agency. The tool's branding is completely removed and replaced with yours. The client never knows (or needs to know) which tool generated the data.</p>

  <p>This matters for several reasons:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Professional perception</strong> — clients expect their agency to have proprietary capabilities and expertise. Delivering a report that visibly comes from Semrush or Ahrefs suggests that the agency is just running a tool anyone could subscribe to. A branded report reinforces the perception that the agency's methodology and analysis are unique.</li>
    <li><strong>Client retention</strong> — when clients associate the audit with your brand rather than a specific tool, they are less likely to try running audits themselves. If they know the report comes from Semrush, they might subscribe directly and question why they need your agency. White-labelling maintains the value of your service layer.</li>
    <li><strong>Consistency across deliverables</strong> — agencies that produce branded reports for SEO, PPC, social media, and web development create a cohesive client experience. A white-labelled audit report that matches your other deliverables in format and branding looks intentional and professional.</li>
    <li><strong>Scalability</strong> — manual report creation does not scale. An agency managing 20 clients cannot produce 20 custom audit reports every quarter without significant analyst time. White-label tools automate the data collection and report generation, freeing your team to focus on interpretation and recommendations.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>The key distinction between white-label reports and simply exporting data from a tool is presentation quality. A CSV export from Screaming Frog is data, not a report. A white-labelled report is a formatted, branded document with executive summaries, visual charts, categorised findings, and actionable recommendations that a non-technical client can understand.</p>

  <h2 id="top-tools">Top Tools</h2>

  <p>The following tools offer the strongest white-label audit capabilities for agencies. Each approaches the problem differently — some are dedicated audit platforms, others are full SEO suites with white-label features, and one is a dedicated reporting layer that connects to multiple data sources.</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Semrush</strong> — the most widely used all-in-one SEO platform with white-label reporting available on the Business plan ($499.95/month). The site audit tool crawls up to 100,000 pages per project, categorises issues by severity, and tracks improvements over time. White-label PDFs include your logo, colours, and custom cover page. The My Reports feature lets you build custom report templates combining audit data with keyword, backlink, and ranking data in a single branded document.</li>
    <li><strong>SE Ranking</strong> — a more affordable alternative that offers white-label capabilities at lower price points. The audit tool covers technical SEO, on-page issues, and Core Web Vitals. White-label reports can be fully branded with your domain, logo, and colour scheme. Unique to SE Ranking is the option to create a white-labelled client portal where clients can log in to see their audit results under your brand.</li>
    <li><strong>AgencyAnalytics</strong> — a dedicated reporting platform designed specifically for agencies. It does not have its own crawl engine but integrates with Google Search Console, Google Analytics, Ahrefs, Semrush, Moz, and dozens of other data sources. Reports are fully white-labelled with customisable dashboards, automated scheduling, and a client-facing portal. Best suited for agencies that already have data sources and need a presentation layer.</li>
    <li><strong>Sitebulb</strong> — a desktop crawler similar to Screaming Frog but with significantly better built-in reporting. Sitebulb generates visual, well-structured audit reports in PDF format that include prioritised hints, explanations of each issue, and affected URL lists. While not traditionally white-labelled (it includes Sitebulb branding in the default reports), the cloud version offers branded reports. The report quality is exceptional — closer to what a human analyst would produce than any other automated tool.</li>
    <li><strong>Raven Tools</strong> — an agency-focused SEO platform with robust white-label reporting. The site auditor covers technical and on-page issues, and reports can be fully branded and scheduled for automatic delivery. Raven's strength is its report builder, which allows you to combine data from multiple sources into a single branded document with custom sections and commentary.</li>
    <li><strong>DashThis</strong> — primarily a dashboard and reporting tool that integrates with SEO data sources. Fully white-labelled dashboards can be shared with clients via custom domain URLs. Less focused on deep audit analysis but excellent for ongoing performance reporting that includes audit metrics.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="feature-comparison">Feature Comparison</h2>

  <p>When evaluating white-label audit tools, these features determine the practical value for agency operations:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Branding depth</strong> — at minimum, you need your logo and colours on reports. Better tools allow custom domains for client portals, branded email notifications, custom cover pages, and removal of all third-party branding including URLs and metadata. Check whether the PDF file properties include the tool's name, as some clients inspect document metadata.</li>
    <li><strong>Report customisation</strong> — can you reorder sections, add custom text, remove irrelevant sections, and include your own strategic commentary? The best tools treat the report as a template you can modify, not a fixed document you can only brand. Agencies need the flexibility to tailor reports to different client types and industries.</li>
    <li><strong>Automated scheduling</strong> — the ability to schedule recurring audits and automatic report delivery saves significant administrative time. Look for tools that let you set crawl frequency (weekly, monthly, quarterly) and automatically email the branded report to your client on a schedule.</li>
    <li><strong>Client portal</strong> — a branded portal where clients can log in to view their audit data, track progress over time, and access historical reports adds a layer of professionalism. SE Ranking and AgencyAnalytics both offer strong client portal features. Semrush provides project sharing but without the same depth of white-labelling.</li>
    <li><strong>Data depth</strong> — the quality of the underlying audit data matters more than the branding. A beautifully branded report with shallow analysis is worse than a plain export with comprehensive data. Evaluate the tool's crawl thoroughness, issue detection range, and ability to integrate Search Console and Analytics data for a complete picture.</li>
    <li><strong>Multi-client management</strong> — agencies need to manage dozens or hundreds of client projects. Check for bulk operations, project templates, team access controls, and the ability to organise clients by team, account manager, or service tier.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="branded-reports">Branded Reports</h2>

  <p>The report itself is the deliverable that clients evaluate, so its quality directly affects perceived agency value. Here is what a well-executed white-label audit report should include:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Custom cover page</strong> — your logo, the client's domain, the audit date, and a professional design that matches your brand identity. First impressions matter, and the cover page sets the tone for the entire document.</li>
    <li><strong>Executive summary</strong> — a one-page overview with key metrics (overall health score, critical issues count, pages crawled, improvement versus previous audit), written in plain language that non-technical stakeholders can understand. The best tools generate this automatically but allow you to edit the text.</li>
    <li><strong>Visual health indicators</strong> — colour-coded charts, score gauges, and trend graphs that communicate site health at a glance. Visual elements make reports more engaging and easier to scan. Check that colours can be customised to match your brand palette.</li>
    <li><strong>Categorised findings</strong> — issues grouped by type (technical, on-page, content, performance) and severity (critical, warning, notice). Each finding should include a clear explanation of what the issue is, why it matters, and how many pages are affected.</li>
    <li><strong>Affected URL lists</strong> — for each issue, a list of the specific URLs affected so the implementation team knows exactly which pages to fix. Reports that say "42 pages have missing meta descriptions" without listing those 42 pages are incomplete.</li>
    <li><strong>Historical comparison</strong> — if this is a recurring audit, include trend data showing how metrics have changed since the previous audit. This demonstrates the value of ongoing SEO work and the progress your agency is delivering.</li>
    <li><strong>Action items</strong> — clear, prioritised recommendations with severity ratings. This is the section that turns an informational report into an actionable document that drives implementation.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="pricing">Pricing</h2>

  <p>White-label features are typically gated behind higher-tier plans. Here is what you can expect to pay for white-label audit capabilities:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Budget tier ($50-100/month)</strong> — SE Ranking and Raven Tools offer white-label features at their mid-tier plans. Suitable for smaller agencies managing five to fifteen clients. Crawl limits and project counts are modest but sufficient for agencies not yet at scale.</li>
    <li><strong>Mid-tier ($100-300/month)</strong> — AgencyAnalytics and DashThis fall in this range, offering strong white-label reporting with generous client/dashboard limits. These tools excel at reporting and client management but may lack the deep crawl capabilities of dedicated SEO platforms.</li>
    <li><strong>Premium tier ($300-500/month)</strong> — Semrush Business and comparable enterprise plans offer the full combination of deep audit data, white-label reporting, and the broader SEO toolkit. The cost is justified for agencies where SEO audits are a core service rather than an occasional add-on.</li>
    <li><strong>Per-report pricing</strong> — some dedicated audit services offer per-report pricing rather than monthly subscriptions. This model works well for agencies that conduct audits infrequently (five to ten per year) and do not want to pay a monthly subscription for a tool they use quarterly.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>Calculate your cost per audit by dividing your monthly tool cost by the number of audits you produce. If you pay $500/month and produce ten audits, each costs $50 in tool fees. If you charge clients $500-1,000 per audit, the margin is healthy. If you produce only two audits per month, the $250 cost per audit eats into your margin significantly.</p>

  <h2 id="how-to-sell-audits">How to Sell Audits</h2>

  <p>White-label audit tools create the foundation for selling audit services as a standalone offering or as a value-add within broader SEO retainers. Here are proven approaches agencies use to monetise their audit capabilities:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Free audit as lead generation</strong> — offer a basic website audit for free to generate new business leads. The free audit demonstrates your expertise, identifies problems the prospect did not know they had, and creates urgency to hire your agency for implementation. Use automated tools for the free version and reserve comprehensive analysis for paying clients.</li>
    <li><strong>Paid standalone audit</strong> — position a detailed audit as a standalone product priced at $500-2,500 depending on site size and depth. Include an expert consultation call to walk through findings. Many clients who purchase standalone audits convert into ongoing retainer clients because the audit reveals more work than they expected.</li>
    <li><strong>Audit as retainer inclusion</strong> — include quarterly audit reports as a standard deliverable in your SEO retainer packages. This provides regular touchpoints to demonstrate progress, identify new issues, and justify the ongoing value of the retainer. Automated scheduling makes this operationally simple once set up.</li>
    <li><strong>Competitive audit upsell</strong> — offer competitive audits that analyse not just the client's site but three to five competitor sites. This adds significant value because it provides strategic intelligence that informs the content and link-building strategy. Price competitive audits at a premium over standard single-site audits.</li>
    <li><strong>Annual audit package</strong> — sell an annual package that includes one comprehensive audit plus three quarterly follow-up reviews. The initial audit establishes the baseline and action plan. Quarterly reviews measure progress and update priorities. Package pricing encourages longer commitments and provides predictable revenue.</li>
    <li><strong>Audit workshops</strong> — for clients who prefer to manage SEO in-house, offer a workshop format where you conduct the audit, present the findings in a half-day session, and train the client's team on how to implement the recommendations. This commands higher prices because it includes education alongside the analysis.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>The most successful agency audit services combine tool-generated data with human analysis and strategic recommendations. The tool handles the data collection and report formatting. Your team adds the interpretation, competitive context, and prioritised recommendations that transform data into a strategy. That human layer is what clients pay for, and it is what differentiates your service from the DIY tools your clients could subscribe to themselves.</p>
